caption: Finally gave this place a try last night (a regular disconnect between listed hours online and available/unavailable dining options has made it difficult to actually give them a shot before this) and the food was awesome! Got carryout but had nothing but pleasant interactions with the servers while placing and collecting our order. Very much look forward to dining in sometime soon, and will be back for the steak burrito for sure.  Despite what Google says as of right now (26 Mar), they ARE open for dine-in, and the server anticipates the patio will be open in approximately one month.
Always a good time at Mi Tocaya Antojería. They have the best margaritas and chimichangas! Great atmosphere!
We are so happy to be back! Diana's good and salsa never disappoint.  Amazing and memorable, as always!

Generally a wait, and the place is pretty intimate so I'm not sure how they handle COVID.  However, the Guac and Steak Burrito are easily the best I've ever had in any city. Even the spicy sauce...amazing.  The Margs put you on your butt.  Excellent food and experience!
This place is absolutely amazing!! Every chicagoan needs to try this place at least once, you will not be disappointed!

Just really good traditional Mexican favorites with a gourmet twist of a super creative mind. Love the space and the attentive waitstaff. The summer patio space is so much fun. A Logan Square favorite, for sure!
great food and service

Eating here is like going to your Abuela’s house, the food is seasoned with a type of love that can’t be replicated.  Found them before the pandemic and started coming in often, Ulises, the head bartender at the time was extremely awesome!  When the pandemic hit, we’ve kept ordering at least once a month because we truly can’t get enough.  This past week we ordered pick for the new cocktails with a few of the dishes and, let me tell you. What an experience.  Must. Haves!

I really enjoyed this place. The menu is a bit small to begin with and this particular night they didn’t have 2 of the menu items. It’s also a bit pricey and even though we loved most of what we ordered, the camarones al mojo de ajo were a bit disappointing. They weren’t bad, it just wasn’t what I was expecting. Never quite seen them served that way. But the drinks were delicious and the covid accommodations were appreciated.

Mi tacoya is one of my favorite Mexican places in the city. The dishes are so flavorful and creative. I’ve never had one dish that I didn’t enjoy. My favorite was their fried oysters but I haven’t seen it back on the menu since I got it so so long ago! Their caldo de res is also fabulous.

The food is fantastic. This is not your typical Mexican food joint so don't expect basic tacos or burritos. The food is prepared and presented perfectly. The atmosphere and staff are great. Highly recommend this place if you're looking to experience Mexican cuisine in a different way.
This place is awesome, very authentic. The patio is very chill, they have a garden next door they bring in the herbs and veggies from!
The food was absolutely wonderful, thank you!
AMAZING
Amazing.  We had the take out picnic. Everything was packaged and presented perfectly. The steak and ribs are tender and delicious, ceviche was flavorful, and the salad refreshing.

I have eaten at Mi Tocaya perhaps 10 times over three years.  It does what it does extremely well, and if anything, the food gets better and better.  Most recently, I went as Chicago emerged from lockdown.  There wasn't a table, so they loaned us blankets to eat on the grass, and took exceptional care when they might have given us takeout.  Everything about the place reflects dedication.
Great patio and food

Fantastic menu, great bar program, but no fussiness or pretension. Family feel but not in the suffocating corporate way—this feels genuine. Hoping to visit again someday after things are safer and they’re back open (COVID19.) My favourite Chicago restaurant

The food is very good here. I love the steak burrito and order every time I come here. Good prices and excellent service. Definitely will keep coming back.

Great selection of mezcal and other cocktails. Definitely try the mezcal sampler if you're new to mezcal.  They offer an interesting take on tacos. Two of the favorites are the milpa and campechano tacos. The milpa taco was quite the surprise, highly recommend it, it's a vegan option and tastes delicious! The tuetano is something different you may not find at other Mexican/Latin American style restaurants, give it a try!  Their churro con crema batida are delicious. They've offered Horchata flavored cream/pudding and it's been delicious! They also offer kristoffer's tres leches cake, probably the best tres leches cake in town. Give it a try here or visit them in Pilsen.  Antojeria is quite a unique spot in Chicago, offering an interesting take on the Mexican/Latin American cultural experience through their unique dishes and mezcal offerings. Their staff is highly attentive and friendly.  Encourage you to make a reservation as it's quite a small spot.

This place would make it in Mexico city--it is that good. Although the place is bustling, the staff run the place with expertise and skill. Not sure who was lying either the host or the manager... I called 20 minutes before at 7:15 and asked if there was availability and the host said yes. Showed up with my fiancé, my brother and my sister in law. The host said there was no seating available although half the restaurant was open... I asked why they couldn’t seat us and the manager said the oven was broken as the kitchen staff was clearly operating the oven and they were seating a reservation at the time. How are you seating a current reservation and the kitchen staff is clearly pulling something out of the oven, but you can’t seat us with half the restaurant open because the oven isn’t operating....would have been fine if they just said the kitchen was closed instead of blatantly lying to us.It was embarrassing and an obvious blatant lie.

Mi tocaya offers one of the most creative takes on Mexican cuisine. Located in a beautiful neighborhood of Logan Square, the location features a gorgeous outdoor patio. The space inside is cozy and decorated with beautiful art showcasing Mexican themes. The Mexican cuisine is one of the most delicious takes on small plates and more common tacos and burritos. All food was bursting with flavors and very fresh. Highly recommended!!!

I want to give 5 stars but i just can't. I really wanted to avoid posting a review because the lack of common sense of 1 temporary employee shouldn't hurt the overall view but let's be fair here, if i am the owner that hostess would be fired on the spot. The chef and owner is a super nice person, the food was very delicious and original! The interior is nice for a hood joint. My office is very close so we went there without a reservation. Upon arrival the host did not tell us that high top tables AND the bar has a wait list(something i hear for the very first time for a...bar) so we were told that it will take 40-50 minutes. Me and my friend decided to wait and grab a beer at the one open space at the bar. The hostess at some point rearranged the clients at the bar and we had to move our jackets to another open bar stool. The hostess came, picked my jacket with 2 fingers and asked in a very condescending tone to whom it belong. I took it and she just turned around and left. I went to her and kindly told her that i do not understand her attitude and asked why is she being so rude, disrespectful and dismissive ever since we came in(omg without a reservation, so sorry we made your unimaginable 5-hour work shift so hard to bear). At that point I had observed 3 tables sitting open for 38 min, 31 min, and 27 min(yes, i have photographic memory). After 1 hour and 37 minutes we sat at the bar frustrated and ate. Cooking and going to restaurants is my hobby and I've never had to deal with such a grumpy, sad, angry, disrespectful, rude host. I will be happy to go there again as i don't hold grudges and because the chef came to us and discussed in great lenght the eve. To top it off, i recommend this place with both hands but please do make a reservation, otherwise you risk to be labeled impatient for not be willing to take the host treatment.

This is probably my favorite restaurant in Chicago. It is actually the first place I went when I moved here. Everything they have is good. The guacamole is unique and delicious. All the small dishes are creative and so tasty you'll just want to keep ordering more. If you go with a group I highly recommend getting a pitcher of margarita. It's great value and there's no ice in the pitcher so it doesn't get watered down while it sits on the table. Also every Sunday they have a completely different menu geared towards family style eating. I recommend the beef stew if you go on Sunday. You really can't go wrong here. I would go out of my way to eat here.

Really enjoyed our meal here. The food was interesting and had great flavor. The service was great the whole time, even when it got busy. We didn't have a reservation so we initially sat at the bar, but they let us move to a table when they got a cancellation, which I appreciated. It is expensive for small plates, so as long as you know that going in to it.

Mi Tocaya Antojería was amazing. I've been wanting to come here forever but never planned far enough in advance and because of the small space, seating is limited. The menu is interesting and they have a lot of vegetarian options. Food comes out as it is ready which sets a nice pace for your meal. Even the guacamole was outstanding- so simple and incredible. The service was great. The margarita was great. I loved the taco that I tried- I would go back just for that. The cactus fundido was so flavorful and delicious served with beautiful tortillas. We ordered the short rib and bone marrow and didn't particularly enjoy it as much as some of the other dishes. The dish wasn't as flavorful as others but the bone marrow was perfectly cooked and it was just the last dish we received and kind of disappointing. The empanandas were delicious as well. The tres leches was good, but also kind of disappointing compared to the rest of our meal. I can't wait to go back- to try some other dishes and get more tacos and guac.

"El que hambre tiene, en tortilla piensa."  I'll preface my review by saying I am Mexican and consider myself a foodie. I have been wanting to visit this restaurant for so long and heard so many great reviews. The atmosphere, loud music, and decor inside was cool but my husband and I sat outside. When we sat down I was surprised that they don't automatically bring out chips and salsa to the table so we ordered the guacamole. I honestly didn't think the ash added much but it was ok.The chips on the other hand, tasted funny. I couldn't quite make out what it was but I suspect it was the frying oil. We both ordered the Doña Irma cocktail and it was one of the best cocktails my husband and I have ever had. I highly recommend it. We went on a Sunday so we did the shareable Cochinta Pibil. The pork was delicious and tender, but the black beans were just ok. What really disappointed me, were the tortillas. I was expecting homemade tortillas from a James Beard nominee. We were served barely-warm tortillas nejas that I have sitting at home. At the time, I even had homemade tortillas in my fridge so I was even more disappointed. I also prefer tortillas nejas to be cooked over an open flame but that's just my personal preference. Overall, if I lived in the neighborhood I would eat here all the time but I do not think it is worth the trip if it's out of your way.

So disappointed, this happened on a Friday night sept 19, service horrible, starting by the hostess 2 ladies one short and a tall , they were rude, i understand they were busy, but cocktails order was taken after 17 min , after 10 min cocktails came to the wrong table, another 10 min, basically we had 3 different servers, all had different orders, had to canceled the last item because took so long,  we order desserts I will say they save the night, they were not good but at least we had something sweet From the bitter experience, I was so exited to have dinner there, that’s why I brought my friends there, such a mistake, a taqueria could make it better, we all 3 work in the industry,  at five stars I’m Mexican and beside that I’m a chef I can tell this place is over rated, can tell they take advantage of the gringos, that’s sad . Searched for best restaurants in Chicago and got out of the center and the too trendy Fulton Market (when I heard the wannabe's talking about Coachella in the bathroom I was over that area). We tried all of the tacos, fundido, salad, and fish. Enjoyed everything thoroughly. What was most surprising was how good the vegetable taco was, even compared to the mixed pork taco. There is a nice patio and a small bar seating area where you can watch the food prep.

2 Stars For the horrible service we received, 5 stars for the food.  We were seated and not offered water or greeted for over 10 minutes.  (They were not busy) We ordered an appetizer and drinks.  We received 2 of the 3 drinks, appetizer was delicious.   We ordered dinner, once again we ordered 3 meals and received 2.  The 3rd arrived 15 minutes after we received the other 2 and still had not received the 3rd drink.  We had finished our dinner, Water & drinks and had to flag down the waiter to ask for more water-45 minutes after we had been seated.  Our waiter had NO clue about what was going on at his table again- The restaurant was not busy and totally no excuse for the service we received. The food was amazing.  Absolutely the best mole we have ever eaten.  Quality ingredients, perfectly spice ratios, and great cocktails. We ate on a Sunday which has a different menu than the rest of the week (no tacos and a few different items) and I can't wait to come back and try the weekday menu!
The beef tongue is a must have, a little bit pricey but very good taste.
Old fashioned Mexican food with a new twist
Great authentic Mexican food. Our waiter Matt was very helpful and knowledgeable of the menu. The Margheritas by the bottle are also great. Highly recommended.
1st time in this place nice place foods good  delicioso
Innovative mexican food with some classic twists. Great place all around.
Wonderful service, great drinks and delicious food.  Street parking is difficult so be prepared to circle.

We went here after reading a review and decided to check it out.  Got here at 20 minutes to 5 and they open at 5.  We were surprised to see there was a line of people waiting to get in. I thought wow, this place must be really good!  Boy was I wrong.  We were asked if we had reservations, when we said no, the hostess said the only tables she had available were outside, at the bar, or at the communal table.  We opted for the communal table which seats 6.  I knew we were in trouble when the waiter brought us water and it was lukewarm.  The waiter explained the concept of the restaurant to us and said that the idea is that it is small and medium tapas to share. This was really code words for very small portions and way overpriced.  We had an Fried oyster taco (con salsa Veracruzana) and a Baja tostada (shrimp erizo de mar, chilica) to start.  I did not find any oysters in my taco at all, and the sauce tasted like tomatoe paste out of the can. The Tostada was good, but nothing great.  Our main dishes were Habichuelas De La Olla con Carnitas (duck carnitas, white beans, green tomato pico de gallo) and  Lobster Esquites (corn, crema enchilada, epazote).  The duck was overcooked and the elote (very small corn cobs)in the Lobster dish was burned.  Our bill was $65.20 before the tip, outrageous!  Even worse, I went to the bathroom, there was just enough toilet paper for me and no replacement roll in sight.  They just opened, what the heck?  When we left, an hour later, the outside patio was packed, but the inside was 3/4 empty.  Where were all the reservations?  Definately not going back there.
That place was awesome

Well deserved reputation and lively ambience. Delicious duck carnitas, oyster tacos, and peanut butter y lengua show the creativity of the chef and are the highlights of a well-thought out and focused menu.
Great food, great staff!  Got to try a ton of Mexican dishes I have never seen before in the states
Awesome place.  I would highly suggest making a reservation before going since seating is limited.  The food is top notch.
Amazing experience!
This was so good. I can't wait to go back!
Really unique food in a funky setting.  A little loud but great waitstaff
Great service, a hip scene, and tasty food.
10/10 cocktails and food. A bit small for the price you pay
In love! Viva Mexico!
Excellent food!

This place is awesome! I would have given them 5 stars but the wine selection is way too limited considering the creativity and quality of the food! The service was right on. Decor is funky but it works! I highly recommend this little jewel!

Been to this place twice now and I have not had a single thing I didn't like. Their plates are kind of small so we always follow their recommendation of picking a few plates to share. Plan to book a weekend dinner reservation well in advance because the place is small and people love it, myself included! A little bit on the pricey side but the great food and awesome service is well worth it! Can't wait to go back!

The food was delicious but the restaurant is small so expect a long wait without a  reservation. We waited more than 75 minutes for a table for 2 early on a Sunday evening until we realized the hostess forgot about us. When we checked back with her she was able to seat us and apologized. Also, the server forgot to bring us one dish we ordered and charged us for it but corrected the problem. Despite the hiccups, we will definitely go back to try more dishes and make a reservation next time.
Pretty good, but as far as upscale Mexican I think the competition is tough

Service was slow and we didn't get everything we ordered, but the guac,  duck carnitas, and tres leche cake were amazing. Mixed bag probably not worth the reservations we got weeks in advance but will likely be back for the three dishes I mentioned.
Excellent high end Mexican,  but with some value items like the tacos.
Great food and drinks.
Great little spot with outdoor seating area. Cocktails were good and the mole is delicious! A little pricey.

Visited with my wife, we really loved it. The draft cocktails where great. We didn't have anything we didn't like. My only complaint is that the servings are all small plates so you  need  to order a lot. We'llack, though we'll make sure to make a reservation.
Great food and service.
Great food love taking people out to eat here

Opened in March and is a great addition to the neighborhood, great cocktails served in a smallish dining space. But it has a great outdoor patio and that is where you want to be! Try the duck carnitas! It doesn't get 5 stars because the food is really good but not great
Ensalada de nopales is fantastic.ceviche is awesome. Aguachile also very good. Watercress excellent touch. Great balance...!
Great food.  Helpful wait staff.

Chef Diana Davila and her team is beyond amazing. Everything that we ordered was delicious! The homemade tortilla chips and excellent salsa, the ceviche, lengua, bone marrow dish, white fish with mole verde sauce, lobster and corn dish, and tres leches...wow. Stellar and everything looks like beautiful art. Fresh ingredients and depths of flavors that you definitely will not get at Rick Bayless' or any other well known mexican place. My husband and I cannot wait to go back! Mi Tocaya is one of the best places in the city.
Amaxing, innovative food based on traditional dishes

The food is really good. I went on a sunday had a burrito, corn & ceviche. Very Small portions, though. drinks are ok nothing to brag about. Its very expensive for the small portions. The staff is very nice. Make reservations to make sure you get a table.

Overall: Mi Tocaya gives a great combination of flavors, just be prepared to pay.  The good: The food is fantastic, whether it's the peanut butter lengua, oyster and milpa tacos, duck leg "carnitas style", or the salpicon de pollo. All were flavorful, unique, and authentic. The menu size is perfect, not too overwhelming yet not too simple. The service was friendly and attentive and while not huge, the atmosphere is fun and inviting. Plus a patio!  The not-so-good: The prices are too high - $44 for a pitcher of margarita? (The cheapest one). A little absurd. Some of the large plates are too costly as well. $55 for one person is too much.  Atmosphere: 8/10 Service: 8/10 Food: 8/10
You want the beer can chicken tacos. Repeat.  Beer can chicken tacos.

Not sure if it gets much better than this for this style of food in Chicago, this place is neck and neck with Rick Bayless’ offerings. A little more relaxed service though, which was refreshing. Mezcal old fashioned, queso fundido and bone marrow / short rib tacos were highlights. Worth going back to try everything on the menu.
I don't know how to describe the food here except awesome. We were in the mood for vegetable-heavy dishes but boy, did they deliver some seriously flavourful dishes.
Amazing Food, Drinks and very friendly staff!
Delicious food, festive atmosphere, and always fantastic service. Share plate menu changes seasonally, with a great base menu of tacos and appetizers. Reasonable prices to boot.

Awesome food. Awesome.  The space is a little tight. And I’m a little upset the michelada didn’t have a salt rim, and no salt in the table or bar.. but that’s minor stuff, go before it gets too popular.  And kristoffers tres leches! Thumbs up..
